As practice for doing linear transformations, we will create the
matrices anyway and show that they lead to the same conclusion as going
step by step in
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2011/Question_A15/Solution_1}{Solution
1}. First recall that a rotation matrix rotating counter-clockwise with
an angle $\theta$ has the form

\begin{align*}A=\begin{bmatrix}
\cos(\theta)  &  -\sin(\theta)\\
\sin(\theta)  &  \cos(\theta)
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

If you are having trouble remembering how to form a rotation matrix, see
the solution to
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2011/Question_A28}{Question
A28} on this exam for a more detailed explanation of these entries (they
are components of the vectors generated by rotating the unit vectors).

Since in this example the angle rotating is $\pi/6$ then we get

\begin{align*}A=\frac{1}{2}\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{3}  &  -1\\
1  &  \sqrt{3}
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Next for the projection matrix, to get the entries in column k, we have
to do a projection of the kth unit vector onto our desired vector
\textbf{u}={[}1,2{]}. We get that the first column is

\begin{align*}\textrm{proj}_\mathbf{u}[1,0]=\frac{[1,0]\cdot[1,2]}{5}[1,2]=\frac{1}{5}[1,2].\end{align*}

The second column is

\begin{align*}\textrm{proj}_\mathbf{u}[0,1]=\frac{[0,1]\cdot[1,2]}{5}[1,2]=\frac{2}{5}[1,2].\end{align*}

Therefore we get that the projection matrix is

\begin{align*}B=\frac{1}{5}
\begin{bmatrix}
1  &  2\\
2  &  4
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

The total transformation then is (remember that the rotation is applied
first),

\begin{align*}
T&=BA=
\frac{1}{10}
\begin{bmatrix}
1  &  2\\
2  &  4
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{3}  &  -1\\
1  &  \sqrt{3}
\end{bmatrix}
\\
&=
\frac{1}{10}
\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{3}+2  &  2\sqrt{3}-1\\
2\sqrt{3}+4  &  4\sqrt{3}-2
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}.

Therefore,

\begin{align*}
T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}\right)&=
\frac{1}{10}
\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{3}+2  &  2\sqrt{3}-1\\
2\sqrt{3}+4  &  4\sqrt{3}-2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
\\
&=
\frac{1}{10}
\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{3}+2\\
2\sqrt{3}+4
\end{bmatrix}
=
\frac{\sqrt{3}+2}{10}\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

like we recovered in the first solution.
